{"id":"mai-bwzg","kind":"ticket","type":"epic","title":"Epic: mai substrate separation — binary split + plugin discovery","priority":1,"tags":["epic","architecture","substrate"],"body":"Parent ADR: mai-tlv9 (ADR: mai as substrate, domain tools as separate binaries)\n\n## Context\n\npkg/docs extraction is done (e252687). The layer violation is fixed — pkg/notes no longer imports pkg/crdt, boundary tests enforce this.\n\nNow we need the binary separation: domain tools become separate binaries, discoverable via plugin manifest. This is the \"guardrail and explicit\" part the hooman asked for.\n\n## What's left\n\n1. Subcommand discovery — mai X tries mai-X on PATH via explicit plugin manifest\n2. mai-pr — extract cmd/mai/pr.go into its own binary\n3. mai-docs — extract cmd/mai/daemon.go + cmd/mai/lattice.go into its own binary\n4. mai-changelog — new tool replacing tinychange\n5. CI boundary check — go list import guard in CI\n\n## Depends on\n\n- mai-tlv9 (ADR — the decision)\n- e252687 (pkg/docs extraction — the foundation)\n\n## Goal\nAll domain tools are separate binaries consuming mai's substrate via Engine interface + plugin manifest\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] mai binary contains only substrate commands + zero-logic shortcuts\n- [ ] mai-pr, mai-docs, mai-changelog are separate binaries\n- [ ] Plugin manifest controls discovery — no magic PATH scanning\n- [ ] All binaries installable from same Go module\n- [ ] CI enforces pkg/notes import boundary\n\n## Verification\n- [ ] go build ./cmd/mai-pr/ ./cmd/mai-docs/ ./cmd/mai-changelog/ all succeed\n- [ ] mai pr dispatches to mai-pr via manifest\n- [ ] Removing mai-pr from PATH makes mai pr show helpful error\n- [ ] go test ./... passes\n- [ ] pkg/notes has zero domain imports (CI check passes)","timestamp":"2026-04-04T13:13:36Z","branch":"main"}

